---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const releaseUrl = "https://github.com/ComputelessComputer/openbird/releases/latest";
const sourceUrl = "https://github.com/ComputelessComputer/openbird";

const detailItems = [
  "Local-first by default. No account required. No backend required.",
  "Captures the frontmost app, window title, browser URL when available, visible accessibility text, and timestamps.",
  "Does not capture raw key events, clipboard contents, passwords, secure text fields, hidden windows, or automatic screenshots.",
  "Stores captured data locally at `~/Library/Application Support/Openbird/openbird.sqlite`.",
  "Supports Ollama, LM Studio, and other OpenAI-compatible endpoints.",
  "Built for macOS 14+ on Apple Silicon.",
];
---

<BaseLayout description="Openbird is a local-first macOS activity journal that captures your current work context, stores it locally, and turns it into a daily review and follow-up chat.">
  <main class="page">
    <div class="header">
      <img src="/openbird.png" alt="Openbird bird illustration" class="header-icon" />
      <div class="header-copy">
        <h1>Openbird</h1>
        <h2>A local-first activity journal for your Mac</h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>
      <a href={releaseUrl}>Download the latest release here</a>. Openbird watches your current work
      context through the Accessibility API, stores that context on your Mac, and turns it into a daily
      review and follow-up chat.
    </p>

    <p>
      It exists because software with this much visibility into your day should not be a black box. If
      an app can see what you are doing across your computer, you should be able to inspect it, control
      it, pause it, and delete its data.
    </p>

    <p>
      Openbird captures the frontmost app and window, builds a local timeline of your day, and uses
      that log to answer questions like what you did today, what you were working on around 3pm, which
      project took most of your attention, and which apps, tabs, or docs were involved in a given block
      of time.
    </p>

    <p>
      The privacy boundary is explicit. The model is your choice. The code is open source because trust
      is better when it is verifiable.
    </p>

    <p>
      Openbird is available now.
      <a href={releaseUrl}>Download the latest release</a>.
      <a href={sourceUrl}>Read the source code on GitHub</a>.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>Details</h2>

    <ul>
      {detailItems.map((item) => (
        <li set:html={item}></li>
      ))}
    </ul>

    <p>
      You can run fully offline if your model is local. Default local endpoints are
      <code>http://127.0.0.1:11434/v1</code> for Ollama and <code>http://127.0.0.1:1234/v1</code> for
      LM Studio.
    </p>

    <p>
      The current app has four main surfaces: onboarding for permissions and privacy, Today for daily
      review generation, Chat for follow-up questions over your local activity history, and Settings for
      provider setup, exclusions, retention, pause, and delete controls.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <h2>FAQ</h2>

    <h3>Why Openbird?</h3>
    <p>
      Because software that observes your work should be inspectable. The point is not “trust us.” The
      point is that you do not have to.
    </p>

    <h3>What does Openbird capture?</h3>
    <p>
      Openbird captures the frontmost app, bundle ID, window title, browser tab URL when available,
      visible text from the active window accessibility tree, and start and end timestamps.
    </p>

    <h3>What does Openbird not capture?</h3>
    <p>
      It does not capture raw key events, clipboard contents, passwords, secure text fields, hidden or
      minimized windows, or automatic screenshots.
    </p>

    <h3>Can I inspect or delete the data?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. You can pause capture at any time, exclude apps and domains, inspect the raw log used for
      generation, and delete the last hour, the last day, or everything.
    </p>

    <h3>Can I use my own model?</h3>
    <p>
      Yes. Openbird supports Ollama, LM Studio, and other OpenAI-compatible endpoints. You can run fully
      offline if your model is local.
    </p>

    <h3>How do I install it?</h3>
    <p>
      Download the latest DMG, drag <code>Openbird.app</code> into Applications, launch it, grant
      Accessibility permission when prompted, choose a provider in Settings, then generate your first
      review from the Today screen.
    </p>

    <p class="small muted">
      Openbird is a local-first macOS activity journal.
      <a href={releaseUrl}>Latest release</a>.
      <a href={sourceUrl}>Source code</a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
